<subSubSection lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,1690,2041]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1690,1716]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
A pair of processes on male abdominal sternite VI short (&lt;
<quantity box="[945,1052,1690,1717]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" unit="mm" value="0.05">0.05 mm</quantity>
), nearly parallel and straight (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="13.[151,250,1780,1804]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetId="figure-18@13.[151,1435,181,1757]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURE 9. Male abdominal sternite VIs of Colocasiomyia colocasiae (Duda) (B in anteroventral view, C in lateral view), C. stamenicola (Carson &amp; Okada) (D in anterior view) and all species of the C. cristata subgroup (A in ventral view, E‒R in anterior view): A, C. ecornuta sp. nov.; E, C. grandis sp. nov.; F, C. vieti sp. nov.; G, C. cristata de Meijere; H, C. matthewsi sp. nov.; I, C. sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso; J, C. kinabaluana sp. nov.; K, C. kotana sp. nov.; L, C. sabahana sp. nov.; M, C. sarawakana sp. nov.; N, C. pistilicola (Carson &amp; Okada); O, C. xenalocasiae (Okada); P, C. diconica (Toda &amp; Okada); Q, C. sumatrana sp. nov.; and R, C. leucocasiae sp. nov. Scale bars: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766420/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 9I</figureCitation>
). Phallal sheath apically vertically dilated in lateral view, subapically with a pair of small, triangular flaps (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 20D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1437,1690,2041]" lastBlockId="31.[151,1437,151,645]" lastPageId="31" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,527,1798,1824]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Supplementary description</emphasis>
(not repeating characters common to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Meijere" authorityYear="1914" box="[970,1092,1798,1824]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Colocasiomyia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis box="[970,989,1798,1824]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1006,1092,1799,1824]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">cristata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Supracervical setae 5–9 per side. Cibarial, medial sensilla approximately 2 per side. Supralateral seta outside prementum approximately 5 per side. Male abdominal sternite III longer than wide; IV posteriorly slightly widening (
<figureCitation box="[1104,1209,1870,1896]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 20A</figureCitation>
). Female abdominal sternite VI as wide as long, medially concaved on posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[912,1014,1906,1932]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 20B</figureCitation>
). Epandrium with 1–3 setae on lateral to dorsal portion and 22–23 setae thicker than cercal setae on ventral portion of each side (
<figureCitation box="[1177,1281,1942,1968]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 20C</figureCitation>
). Cercus with approximately 34–39 setae (
<figureCitation box="[473,578,1978,2004]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 20C</figureCitation>
). Oviscapt distally slightly curved ventrad, longer than phallus (apodeme + sheath), with 20–22 ovisensilla but no patch of pubescence (
<figureCitation box="[827,927,2014,2040]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Fig. 20F</figureCitation>
). Puparium (3rd instar larva): segments with stout spicules on ventral surface; anterior spiracle sessile, with a bundle of approximately 4 short branches; caudal segments elongate, with many small spicules, ending in a V-shaped pair of posterior spiracles (
<figureCitation box="[1211,1342,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 20G,H</figureCitation>
). Mouth hook less expanded medioventrally in lateral view; distal blade as long as basal portion, apically pointed, weakly curved downward, with two rows of small, acute teeth on submedial to subapical portion of ventral margin (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="30.[151,250,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[203,1385,181,1830]" captionTargetId="figure-22@30.[203,1385,181,1831]" captionTargetPageId="30" captionText="FIGURE 20. Colocasiomyia sulawesiana Okada &amp; Yafuso (♂, ♀ and puparium from Enrekang, South Sulawesi, Indonesia). A, Male abdominal sternites (ventral view); B, female abdominal sternites (ventral view); C, periphallic organs (lateral view); D, phallic organs (lateral view); E, ditto (ventral view); F, female terminalia (lateral view); G, anterior spiracles of puparium (dorsal view); H, puparium (ventral habitus; inset: caudal-most portion); I, mouth hook; J, cephalopharyngeal skeleton. Scale bars: 0.1 mm in A–F and J, 1.0 mm in H." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766446" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766446/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 20I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
