<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,439,465]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Remarks.</emphasis>
Some original descriptions by 
<bibRefCitation author="Okada, T. &amp; Yafuso, M." box="[658,922,439,465]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="48 - 55" refId="ref33192" refString="Okada, T. &amp; Yafuso, M. (1989) The genus Colocasiomyia Duda (Diptera, Drosophilidae) from Sulawesi. Proceedings of the Japanese Society of Systematic Zoology, 39, 48 - 55." type="journal article" year="1989">Okada &amp; Yafuso (1989)</bibRefCitation>
should be revised as follows. 
<bibRefCitation author="Okada, T. &amp; Yafuso, M." pageId="31" pageNumber="32" pagination="48 - 55" refId="ref33192" refString="Okada, T. &amp; Yafuso, M. (1989) The genus Colocasiomyia Duda (Diptera, Drosophilidae) from Sulawesi. Proceedings of the Japanese Society of Systematic Zoology, 39, 48 - 55." type="journal article" year="1989">Okada &amp; Yafuso (1989)</bibRefCitation>
described, “Second tarsal joint of fore leg protruded, with about 5 black teeth in 2 rows”, but illustrated four teeth in “ 
<figureCitation box="[317,386,511,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1197,1221]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,182,1171]" captionTargetId="figure-22@6.[151,1435,179,1171]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 1. Alocasia alba Schott in West Java. A, Inflorescences and infructescences at Stages I to VI, except III (see text for explanation of each stage) in a cluster of sequentially blooming inflorescences of a plant at Ciamis; B, a Stage-II inflorescence of a plant at the Bogor Botanical Garden, showing the lower part (pistillate and intermediate regions) of spadix by partly cutting out the spathe and the position of spathal constriction with arrowhead; C, a schema indicating the spadix structure and dissected sections (modified from Carson &amp; Okada 1980: 26; fig.6)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5766404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5766404/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
” and mentioned, “second tarsal joint of fore leg with about 4 teeth”, in the paragraph of ‘ 
<emphasis box="[161,313,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Relationships</emphasis>
’. The latter state should be correct, because all the specimens examined in this study have four pegs on the fore tarsomere II without any exception. The original descriptions of “male 6S laterally divided, without protuberances” and “Surstylus absent” may be due to overlook of these small or vestigial organs in this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
